=n%3A%211000%2Ci%3Astripbooks%2Cp_28%3AInternational%20Conference%20on%20the%20Unity%20of%20the%20Sciences&page=1 ICUS publications]\n*[http://www.wfwp.org Official site of WFWP International]\n\n{{Unification Church}}\n{{New Religious Movements}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unification Church| ]]\n[[Category:1954 establishments in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism]]\n[[Category:Christian new religious movements]]\n", "name_user": "PopSci", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBlessing ceremony and views on sex and family", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unification_movement"}
{"title_page": "Bahaar Aane Tak", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Bahaar Aane Tak<br> \u092c\u0939\u093e\u0930 \u0906\u0928\u0947 \u0924\u0915\n| image = File:Bahaar Aane Tak poster.jpg\n| caption = \n| director = Tariq Shah<ref name=\":0\" />\n| producer = [[Gulshan Kumar]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n| writer = Talat Rekhi<ref name=\":0\" />\n| starring = {{ubl|[[Roopa Ganguly]]|[[Moon Moon Sen]]|[[Sumeet Saigal]]|Tariq Shah}}\n| narrator = \n| music = [[Rajesh Roshan]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n| cinematography = Ajay Prabhakar<ref name=\":0\" />\n| editing = {{ubl|Vinod Nayak|Prashant Khedekar}}<ref name=\":0\" />\n| distributor = \n| released = {{film date|df=y|1990|12|7}}<ref name=\":0\" />\n| runtime = \n| country = [[India]]\n| language = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| budget = \n| gross = \n| image_size = \n| preceded_by = \n| followed_by = \n| website = \n}}\n\n''''' Bahaar Aane Tak ''''' is a [[Bollywood films of 1990|1990]] [[Bollywood]] family drama movie directed by Tariq Shah and produced by [[Gulshan Kumar]]. The cinematographer of this film is Ajay Prabhakar. The film revolves around a man who coincidentally marries a woman who was once raped by his close friend. It stars [[Roopa Ganguly]], [[Moon Moon Sen]], [[Sumeet Saigal]], Tariq Shah, [[Shammi (actress)|Shammi]], [[Ram Mohan]] and [[Navin Nischol]]. The music of the film was composed by [[Rajesh Roshan]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://muvyz.com/moviepage/dd840129/plot/|title=Bahaar Aane Tak (1990) {{!}} Hindi Movie Plot - Bollywood MuVyz|website=Bahaar Aane Tak (1990) {{!}} Hindi Movie Plot - Bollywood MuVyz|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gomolo.com/bahar-aane-tak-movie/6463|title=Bahar Aane Tak (1990)|website=gomolo.com|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://osianama.com/film-titles/bahaar-aane-tak-1990|title=Bahaar Aane Tak|website=osianama.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref>\n\nNotwithstanding an interesting storyline, the movie was a debacle at the box office. The film brought doom to [[Roopa Ganguly]]'s [[Bollywood]] career. The songs from this movie were popular in the 1990s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://filmzack.wordpress.com/2017/05/31/roopa-ganguly/|title=Why Did Roopa Ganguly Fail to Make It into Bollywood|date=2017-05-31|work=Filmzack|access-date=2017-10-03|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nVijay and Raja have been best friends since childhood. Vijay is obedient, honest and hardworking and lives with his mother. He is always haunted by the death of his girlfriend Renu, who died in an accident. Raja is the son of wealthy businessman Mahendra Pratap, who hates his son because his wife died during childbirth. He blames Raja for her death and prefers to not have any relationship with his son. As a result, the task of raising Raja falls on the shoulders of their loyal servant Bansi, who gives Raja the love of a mother and a father.\n\nDespite Bansi's good upbringing, Vijay's mum's love and Vijay's guidance, Raja still grows up to be a philandering playboy who lives a hedonistic lifestyle. Being a loyal friend, Vijay always has to bail his friend out of trouble and he even berates him and urges him to change his womanizing ways, but Raja is incorrigible.\n\nOne day, Vijay's mother meets a kind girl called Rama in the temple and decides to get her married to her son. Vijay reluctantly agrees, without even knowing who the girl is. Because of some important business matter, Raja has to travel to London and so is unable to attend the wedding. On the wedding night, Vijay sees his bride's face for the first time and is quite shocked, as it turns out that Rama is the same girl whom Raja had once raped and Vijay hadn't been able to save her. It immediately became obvious to Vijay that Rama had married him only to exact her revenge as she believed that Vijay was in cahoots with Raja when the latter raped her.\n\nWhen Raja returns from London, he too is shocked to see Rama, but neither Raja nor Vijay can reveal anything to Vijay's mother. The two continue to live their lives while every moment being tormented by what they did to Rama. This inner guilt creates a rift between the two friends and even pushes Vijay into becoming an alcoholic. When Rama learns of Vijay's innocence, she has a change of heart and she and Vijay reconcile. Rama also says that she has chosen to let go of her hate and has forgiven Raja.\n\nRaja however, unaware of this and tormented by his guilt decides to commit suicide by drinking poison. Vijay and Rama rush to Raja's side, but they are too late. Raja eventually dies in his friend's arms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RxfxbipEfcg|title=Bahaar Ane Tak (1990)|website=www.youtube.com|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Roopa Ganguly]] as Rama\n*[[Sumeet Saigal]] as Rajkumar Pratap \"Raja\"\n*[[Moon Moon Sen]] as Renu\n*Tariq Shah as Vijay\n*Ram Mohan as Bansi\n*[[Navin Nischol]] as Mahendra Pratap\n*[[Shammi (actress)|Shammi]] as Vijay's mother<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/movies/bahaar-aane-tak-6966/cast-crew|title=Bahaar Aane Tak (1990) - Full Cast and Crew {{!}} Cinestaan.com|website=www.cinestaan.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\nLyrics written by [[Indivar]].\n{| border=\"10\" cellpadding=\"10\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n!  !! Song !! Singer\n|-\n| 1\n| '''''Mohabbat Inayat Karam Dekhte Hain'''''\n| [[Anuradha Paudwal]], [[Pankaj Udhas]]\n|-\n| 2\n| '''''Kali Teri Choti Hai Paranda'''''\n| [[Anuradha Paudwal]], Mangal Singh\n|-\n| 3\n| '''''Ek Pal Hasna Jo Chaha'''''\n| [[Anwar (singer)|Anwar]]\n|-\n| 4\n| '''''Dil Ke Karib Koi Chhupa Hai'''''\n| [[Talat Aziz]], [[Anuradha Paudwal]]\n|-\n| 5\n| '''''Ye Khamoshi Mere Hum Nashi'''''\n| [[Anuradha Paudwal]], [[Kumar Sanu]]\n|-\n|6\n| '''''Aankhen Aankhen Maikhaana Dil Peene Ko'''''\n| [[Pankaj Udhas]], [[Anuradha Paudwal]]\n|-\n|7\n| '''''Nazar Milata Kabhi Tujhse'''''\n| [[Anuradha Paudwal]], [[Gurcharan]]\n|-\n|8\n| '''''Din Patjhad Ke Ya Bahaare Ho'''''\n| [[Anuradha Paudwal]], [[Manhar Udhas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.47sh20.com/mp3/bahaar-aane-tak-movie-song-download.html|title=Bahaar Aane Tak Movie Song Download {{!}} www.47sh20.com|last=Admin|website=www.47sh20.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0395464}}\n\n[[Category:1990s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:1989 films]]\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Rajesh Roshan]]\n[[Category:1980s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:T-Series films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Bahaar Aane Tak<br> \u092c\u0939\u093e\u0930 \u0906\u0928\u0947 \u0924\u0915\n| image = File:Bahaar Aane Tak poster.jpg\n| caption = \n| director = Tariq Shah<ref name=\":0\" />\n| producer = [[Gulshan Kumar]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n| writer = Talat Rekhi<ref name=\":0\" />\n| starring = {{ubl|[[Roopa Ganguly]]|[[Moon Moon Sen]]|[[Sumeet Saigal]]|Tariq Shah}}\n| narrator = \n| music = [[Rajesh Roshan]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n| cinematography = Ajay Prabhakar<ref name=\":0\" />\n| editing = {{ubl|Vinod Nayak|Prashant Khedekar}}<ref name=\":0\" />\n| distributor = \n| released = {{film date|df=y|1990|12|7}}<ref name=\":0\" />\n| runtime = \n| country = [[India]]\n| language = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| budget = \n| gross = \n| image_size = \n| preceded_by = \n| followed_by = \n| website = \n}}\n\n''''' Bahaar Aane Tak ''''' is a [[Bollywood films of 1990|1990]] [[Bollywood]] family drama movie directed by Tariq Shah and produced by [[Gulshan Kumar]]. The cinematographer of this film is Ajay Prabhakar. The film revolves around a man who coincidentally marries a woman who was once raped by his close friend. It stars [[Roopa Ganguly]], [[Moon Moon Sen]], [[Sumeet Saigal]], Tariq Shah, [[Shammi (actress)|Shammi]], [[Ram Mohan]] and [[Navin Nischol]]. The music of the film was composed by [[Rajesh Roshan]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://muvyz.com/moviepage/dd840129/plot/|title=Bahaar Aane Tak (1990) {{!}} Hindi Movie Plot - Bollywood MuVyz|website=Bahaar Aane Tak (1990) {{!}} Hindi Movie Plot - Bollywood MuVyz|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gomolo.com/bahar-aane-tak-movie/6463|title=Bahar Aane Tak (1990)|website=gomolo.com|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://osianama.com/film-titles/bahaar-aane-tak-1990|title=Bahaar Aane Tak|website=osianama.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref>\n\nNotwithstanding an interesting storyline, the movie was a debacle at the box office. The film brought doom to [[Roopa Ganguly]]'s [[Bollywood]] career. The songs from this movie were extremely popular in the 90s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://filmzack.wordpress.com/2017/05/31/roopa-ganguly/|title=Why Did Roopa Ganguly Fail to Make It into Bollywood|date=2017-05-31|work=Filmzack|access-date=2017-10-03|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nVijay and Raja have been best friends since childhood. Vijay is obedient, honest and hardworking and lives with his mother. He is always haunted by the death of his girlfriend Renu, who died in an accident. Raja is the son of wealthy businessman Mahendra Pratap, who hates his son because his wife died during childbirth. He blames Raja for her death and prefers to not have any relationship with his son. As a result, the task of raising Raja falls on the shoulders of their loyal servant Bansi, who gives Raja the love of a mother and a father.\n\nDespite Bansi's good upbringing, Vijay's mum's love and Vijay's guidance, Raja still grows up to be a philandering playboy who lives a hedonistic lifestyle. Being a loyal friend, Vijay always has to bail his friend out of trouble and he even berates him and urges him to change his womanizing ways, but Raja is incorrigible.\n\nOne day, Vijay's mother meets a kind girl called Rama in the temple and decides to get her married to her son. Vijay reluctantly agrees, without even knowing who the girl is. Because of some important business matter, Raja has to travel to London and so is unable to attend the wedding. On the wedding night, Vijay sees his bride's face for the first time and is quite shocked, as it turns out that Rama is the same girl whom Raja had once raped and Vijay hadn't been able to save her. It immediately became obvious to Vijay that Rama had married him only to exact her revenge as she believed that Vijay was in cahoots with Raja when the latter raped her.\n\nWhen Raja returns from London, he too is shocked to see Rama, but neither Raja nor Vijay can reveal anything to Vijay's mother. The two continue to live their lives while every moment being tormented by what they did to Rama. This inner guilt creates a rift between the two friends and even pushes Vijay into becoming an alcoholic. When Rama learns of Vijay's innocence, she has a change of heart and she and Vijay reconcile. Rama also says that she has chosen to let go of her hate and has forgiven Raja.\n\nRaja however, unaware of this and tormented by his guilt decides to commit suicide by drinking poison. Vijay and Rama rush to Raja's side, but they are too late. Raja eventually dies in his friend's arms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RxfxbipEfcg|title=Bahaar Ane Tak (1990)|website=www.youtube.com|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Roopa Ganguly]] as Rama\n*[[Sumeet Saigal]] as Rajkumar Pratap \"Raja\"\n*[[Moon Moon Sen]] as Renu\n*Tariq Shah as Vijay\n*Ram Mohan as Bansi\n*[[Navin Nischol]] as Mahendra Pratap\n*[[Shammi (actress)|Shammi]] as Vijay's mother<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/movies/bahaar-aane-tak-6966/cast-crew|title=Bahaar Aane Tak (1990) - Full Cast and Crew {{!}} Cinestaan.com|website=www.cinestaan.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\nLyrics written by [[Indivar]].\n{| border=\"10\" cellpadding=\"10\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n!  !! Song !! Singer\n|-\n| 1\n| '''''Mohabbat Inayat Karam Dekhte Hain'''''\n| [[Anuradha Paudwal]], [[Pankaj Udhas]]\n|-\n| 2\n| '''''Kali Teri Choti Hai Paranda'''''\n| [[Anuradha Paudwal]], Mangal Singh\n|-\n| 3\n| '''''Ek Pal Hasna Jo Chaha'''''\n| [[Anwar (singer)|Anwar]]\n|-\n| 4\n| '''''Dil Ke Karib Koi Chhupa Hai'''''\n| [[Talat Aziz]], [[Anuradha Paudwal]]\n|-\n| 5\n| '''''Ye Khamoshi Mere Hum Nashi'''''\n| [[Anuradha Paudwal]], [[Kumar Sanu]]\n|-\n|6\n| '''''Aankhen Aankhen Maikhaana Dil Peene Ko'''''\n| [[Pankaj Udhas]], [[Anuradha Paudwal]]\n|-\n|7\n| '''''Nazar Milata Kabhi Tujhse'''''\n| [[Anuradha Paudwal]], [[Gurcharan]]\n|-\n|8\n| '''''Din Patjhad Ke Ya Bahaare Ho'''''\n| [[Anuradha Paudwal]], [[Manhar Udhas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.47sh20.com/mp3/bahaar-aane-tak-movie-song-download.html|title=Bahaar Aane Tak Movie Song Download {{!}} www.47sh20.com|last=Admin|website=www.47sh20.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0395464}}\n\n[[Category:1990s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:1989 films]]\n[[Category:1990 films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Rajesh Roshan]]\n[[Category:1980s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:T-Series films]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bahaar_Aane_Tak"}
{"title_page": "Gene Deitch", "text_new": "{{short description|American illustrator, animator and film director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Gene Deitch.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = Gene Deitch in 2007\n| name               = Gene Deitch\n| birth_name         = Eugene Merril Deitch\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1924|8|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], {{nowrap|United States}}\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|4|16|1924|8|8}}\n| death_place        = [[Prague]], {{nowrap|[[Czech Republic]]}}\n| nationality        = [[American people|American]]\n| spouse             = Marie Deitch (m. 1943\u2013?)<br>Zdenka Deitchova (n\u00e9e Najmanov\u00e1; m. 1964)\n| children           = 3 (including [[Kim Deitch]])\n| occupation         = Illustrator, animator, director\n| years_active       = 1945\u20132008\n| website            = [https://web.archive.org/web/20180215153432/http://www.genedeitch.com/ Archived at archive.org]\n}}\n'''Eugene Merril Deitch''' (August 8, 1924 \u2013 April 16, 2020) was an [[Americans|American]]-born [[Czech Republic|Czech]] illustrator, [[animator]], comics artist,<ref>https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm</ref> and film director. Based in [[Prague]] since 1959, Deitch was known for creating [[animated cartoon]]s such as ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'', ''[[Tom Terrific]]'', and ''[[Nudnik]]'', as well as his work on the ''[[Popeye]]'' and ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' series.\n\n==Early life==\nDeitch was born in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]] on August 8, 1924, the son of salesman Joseph Deitch and Ruth Delson Deitch.<ref name=\"Lenburg\">{{cite book|last=Lenburg|first=Jeff|title=Who's Who in Animated Cartoons|publisher=[[Applause Theatre and Cinema Books]]|location=New York City|year=2006|edition=Illustrated|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/62 62\u201364]|isbn=978-1-55783-671-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/62}}</ref><ref name=NCSML>{{cite web | url = http://www.ncsml.org/exhibits/gene-deitch/ | title = Gene Deitch (born Eugene Merril Deitch), 1924 | publisher = National Czech and Slovak Museum | accessdate = November 6, 2015 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150912101818/http://www.ncsml.org/exhibits/gene-deitch/ | archivedate = September 12, 2015 | url-status = dead }}</ref> In 1929, the family moved to California, and Deitch attended school in [[Hollywood]]. He graduated from [[Los Angeles High School]] in 1942.\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating, Deitch began working for [[North American Aviation]], drawing aircraft blueprints. In 1943, he was [[military conscription|drafted]] and underwent pilot training before catching [[pneumonia]] and being honorably discharged in May of the following year.<ref name=NCSML /> From 1945 to 1951, Deitch contributed covers and interior art to the [[jazz]] magazine ''The Record Changer''.<ref name=NCSML /> In the 1950s, Deitch was an early supporter and audio engineer for [[Connie Converse]], one of the first American [[singer-songwriter]]s.<ref name=\"The Awl 2010\">{{cite news | url=http://www.theawl.com/2010/08/the-story-of-connie-converse | title=The Story of Connie Converse | date=August 3, 2010 | accessdate=1 June 2013 | last=Jefferson | first=Cord | newspaper=The Awl}}</ref> Converse appeared once on [[CBS]] television due in part to Deitch's connections with the network, but otherwise found little success and eventually abandoned music only to be rediscovered decades later, through recordings Deitch had made of her music in 1954.\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Gene Deitch in 1959.jpg|thumb|Gene Deitch in 1959]] -->\nIn 1955, Deitch took a apprenticeship at the animation studio [[United Productions of America]] (UPA), and later became the creative director of [[Terrytoons]],<ref name=NCSML /> creating such characters as [[Sidney the Elephant]],<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/sidney.htm Sidney the Elephant] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vi9yM3C0?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/sidney.htm |date=January 20, 2015 }} from the original on January 20, 2015.</ref> [[Gaston Le Crayon]],<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/lecrayon.htm Gaston Le Crayon] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/66xEV3BXC?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/lecrayon.htm |date=April 16, 2012 }} from the original on April 16, 2012.</ref> and [[Clint Clobber]].<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/clobber.htm Clint  Clobber] at  [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/66vv3sglC?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/clobber.htm |date=April 15, 2012 }} from the original on April 16, 2012.</ref> Beginning in 1955, while working at UPA, Deitch wrote and drew the [[United Feature Syndicate]] comic strip ''The Real-Great Adventures of Terr\u2019ble Thompson!, Hero of History'', starring a courageous child in fantastical adventures. A skit about Terr'ble Thompson had been recorded by [[Little Golden Records]], with actor [[Art Carney]] and bandleader [[Mitch Miller]] participating. That led to the daily strip, which ran from Sunday, October 16, 1955, to April 14, 1956.<ref name=thompson>[http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm ''The Real-Great Adventures of Terr\u2019ble Thompson!, Hero of History''] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6fEh3AEBM?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |date=February 12, 2016 }} from the original on February 12, 2016.</ref> In early 1958, his theatrical cartoon ''Sidney's Family Tree'' was nominated for an Academy Award. In August 1958, he was fired from Terrytoons and set up his own studio in New York called Gene Deitch Associates, Inc., which primarily produced television commercials.<ref name=NCSML /> \n\nWhen client [[Rembrandt Films]]<ref name=WSJ/> promised to fund ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'', an animated theatrical short Deitch wanted to create, Deitch relocated to the company's base in [[Prague]], [[Czechoslovakia]], in October 1959.<ref name=NCSML /> He originally planned to spend only ten days in Prague, but after meeting his future wife, Zdena, decided to settle permanently in the city.<ref name=DVTV /> ''Munro'' premiered in Czechoslovakia in September 1960 and in the U.S. on October 5, 1961, as a short preceding ''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (film)|Breakfast at Tiffany's]]''. It won an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film|Best Animated Short Film]] in 1961,<ref>{{cite web|title=The 33rd Academy Awards|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1961|publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=November 6, 2015 | quote= Short Subject (Cartoon): Winner - ''Munro'', William L. Snyder, Producer| archivedate=October 15, 2015 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015234831/http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1961 | url-status=live}}</ref> the first short created outside of the United States to be so honored.<ref>[http://www.genedeitch.com/ \"Anatomy of an Oscar\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050303173042/http://www.genedeitch.com/ |date=March 3, 2005 }} ''Occasional Deitch'' 2007, page 3, retrieved [2007-11-04].</ref>\n\nFrom 1960 to 1963, Deitch collaborated with Rembrandt to direct ''[[Popeye the Sailor (1960s TV series)|Popeye]]'' cartoons for television with [[King Features Syndicate|King Features]], and from 1961 to 1962 he directed 13 new ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' shorts for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]].<ref name=WSJ>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/djreprints/access/108884830.html?dids=108884830:108884830&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun+11%2C+1962&author=&pub=Wall+Street+Journal&desc=Popeye%2C+Tom+%26+Jerry+Join+Trend+to+Shift+Production+Overseas&pqatl=google|title=Popeye, Tom & Jerry Join Trend to Shift Production Overseas|accessdate=August 17, 2010|date=June 11, 1962|author=MacDougall, Kent|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Lehman\">{{cite book|title=American Animated Cartoons of the Vietnam Era: A Study of Social Commentary in Films and Television Programs, 1961\u20131973|first=P. Lehman|last=Christopher|isbn=978-0-7864-2818-2|chapter=The Cartoons of 1961\u20131962|pages=23\u201324|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|year=2007}}</ref> Being a \"UPA man\",<ref name=\"Deitch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.awn.com/genedeitch/chapter-twentyone-tom-and-jerry-the-first-reincarnation|title=Tom & Jerry: The First Reincarnation|work=How To Succeed in Animation|publisher=[[Animation World Network]]|year=2001|last=Deitch|first=Gene|accessdate=September 27, 2009 | archivedate= September 14, 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140914223444/http://www.awn.com/genedeitch/chapter-twentyone-tom-and-jerry-the-first-reincarnation | url-status=live}}</ref> Deitch had misgivings about the latter property, thinking they were \"needlessly violent.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\"/> However, after being assigned to work on the series, he quickly realized that \"nobody took [the violence] seriously\", and it was merely \"a parody of exaggerated human emotions.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\">{{cite video |people=Deitch, Gene |date=2015 |title=''Tom and Jerry...and Gene'' in Tom and Jerry: The Gene Deitch Collection |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> He also came to see what he perceived as the \"biblical roots\" in Tom and Jerry's conflict, similar to [[David and Goliath]], stating \"That's where we feel a connection to these cartoons: the little guy can win (or at least survive) to fight another day.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\"/> Contemporary critics often regarded Deitch's shorts as the worst in the ''Tom and Jerry'' series; however, Deitch claims some fans wrote positive letters to him, stating that his ''Tom and Jerry'' shorts were their personal favorites.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rotoscopers.com/2015/06/21/tom-and-jerry-the-gene-deitch-collection-dvd-review/ | title=\u2018Tom and Jerry: The Gene Deitch Collection\u2019 \u2013 DVD Review| publisher= Rotoscopers.com | first= Jonathan |last=North |date= June 21, 2015|accessdate= November 6, 2015| archivedate= September 12, 2015| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912040746/http://www.rotoscopers.com/2015/06/21/tom-and-jerry-the-gene-deitch-collection-dvd-review/ | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith producer [[William L. Snyder]], Deitch co-produced and directed a series of TV shorts of ''[[Krazy Kat]]'' for King Features from 1962 to 1964. ''[[The Bluffers]]'', which was based on one of Deitch's ideas, was also co-produced by him. He directed the 1966 film ''[[Alice of Wonderland in Paris]]''. In 1966, he worked with Czech animator [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Trnka]] on a feature-length animated film adapatation of ''[[The Hobbit]]''. However, producer William L. Snyder couldn't secure the funds, and in order to not let the rights for the novel expire, he asked Deitch to produce a short film adaptation in 30 days. Deitch and illustrator [[Adolf Born]] made a 13-minute animated film never intended for distribution; the film was long considered lost until it was rediscovered by Snyder's son and released on [[YouTube]] in 2012.<ref name=DVTV>{{cite web|url=https://video.aktualne.cz/dvtv/jsi-bud-komunista-nebo-blazen-slychaval-ceskoslovensko-bylo/r~a96bd4a84c8211e880d30cc47ab5f122/?redirected=1526714757|title=Jsi bu\u010f komunista, nebo bl\u00e1zen, sl\u00fdch\u00e1val. \u010ceskoslovensko bylo jako st\u0159edov\u011bk, l\u00ed\u010d\u00ed dr\u017eitel Oscara / 'You are either a communist or a fool': Czechoslovakia was like the Middle Ages, says the Oscar winner| publisher=[[DVTV]]| date= n.d.|accessdate=May 19, 2018|location=Czech Republic|language=czech}}</ref> Also in 1966, Deitch created a young girl adventurer in ''Terr'ble Tessie.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fEh3AEBM?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |archivedate=February 12, 2016 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1969 until his retirement in 2008, Deitch was the leading animation director for the Connecticut organization [[Weston Woods Studios]], adapting children's picture books. Deitch adapted 37 films for Weston Woods, from [[Drummer Hoff|''Drummer Hoff'']] in 1969 to ''Voyage to the Bunny Planet'' in 2008.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cech, John.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/310398653|title=Imagination and innovation : the story of Weston Woods|date=2009|publisher=Scholastic Press|isbn=978-0-545-08922-7|edition=1st ed|location=New York|oclc=310398653}}</ref> His studio was located in Prague near the [[Barrandov Studios]], where many major films were recorded. In 2003, Deitch was awarded the [[Annie Award]]s' [[Winsor McCay Award]] by [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] for a lifetime contribution to the art of animation.<ref name=\"McCayRecipient\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/winsor-mccay-award |title=Winsor McCay Award |publisher=[[Annie Award]]s / [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] |accessdate=November 3, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712035848/http://annieawards.org/winsor-mccay-award |archivedate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDeitch met his first wife, Marie, when they both worked at North American Aviation, and they married in 1943.<ref name=NCSML /> Their three sons,<ref name=NCSML /> [[Kim Deitch|Kim]], [[Simon Deitch|Simon]], and Seth Deitch, are artists and writers for [[underground comix]] and [[alternative comics]].<ref name=lam-kim>{{cite web |url=http://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch.htm |title=Kim Deitch |website=[[Lambiek Comiclopedia]] |access-date=November 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907063815/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch.htm |archive-date=September 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1960, several days after arriving in Prague in October 1959, Deitch met Zdenka Najmanov\u00e1, the production manager at the studio [[Brat\u0159i v triku]] where he worked. They married in 1964.<ref name=NCSML /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.novinky.cz/zena/styl/469454-gene-deitch-ze-bych-zustal-v-ceskoslovensku-zit-tehdy-nikoho-nenapadlo.html| title=Gene Deitch: \u017de bych z\u016fstal v \u010ceskoslovensku \u017e\u00edt, tehdy nikoho nenapadlo / Gene Deitch: I would live in Czechoslovakia, then did not think anyone| date=May 5, 2018|accessdate=May 19, 2018|first=Lucie |last=Jandov\u00e1|work=[[Pr\u00e1vo]]|location=Czech Republic|language=czech| via=Novinky.cz|archivedate=May 5, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180505080129/https://www.novinky.cz/zena/styl/469454-gene-deitch-ze-bych-zustal-v-ceskoslovensku-zit-tehdy-nikoho-nenapadlo.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Deitch's memoir, ''For the Love of Prague,'' is based on his experience of being what he called \"the only free American living and working in Prague during 30 years of the Communist Party dictatorship.\"<ref>Deitch, G., [http://www.praguepost.com/142-culture/51247-gene-deitch-s-memoir-is-back ''For the Love of Prague''], 6th edition (Prague: John Caullkins, 2015).</ref> According to Deitch, although he was followed by the [[StB]] and his phone was tapped, he was never aware of their presence and was never interrogated nor arrested.<ref name=DVTV />\n\nDeitch died of natural causes in Prague on April 16, 2020, at the age of 95.<ref>[https://news.expats.cz/weekly-czech-news/american-animator-longtime-prague-expat-gene-deitch-passes-away-at-age-95/ American animator, longtime Prague expat Gene Deitch passes away at age 95]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\nKevin Scott Collier. ''The Amazing Transformations of Tom Terrific''. CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform, 2017. {{ISBN|1974583899}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.genedeitch.com}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20150801130220/http://genedeitch.com/ Archived] from the original on August 1, 2015,\n*[http://www.genedeitchcredits.com/ Gene Deitch Credits] (additional official site) [https://web.archive.org/web/20150922191020/http://genedeitchcredits.com/ Archived] from the original on September 22, 2015.\n*{{IMDb name|id=0215126|name=Gene Deitch}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150908062347/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm Gene Deitch] at the Lambiek Comiclopedia. Retrieved on November 6, 2013. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150908062347/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm Archived] at the Lambiek Comiclopedia. Retrieved on November 6, 2013. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150908062347/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm Archived] from the original on September 8, 2015.\n*{{cite web| url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/brewtv/howdydoody-22435.html | author= [[Jerry Beck|Beck, Jerry]], and Amidi, Amid, eds. | publisher= [[Cartoon Brew]] | title= TV #22: 'Howdy Doody and His Magic Hat' (1953)| date= April 15, 2010| accessdate= October 29, 2015| archivedate= March 8, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120308104239/http://www.cartoonbrew.com/brewtv/howdydoody.html | url-status=live}} Includes biographical sidebar by Deitch.\n*{{cite web | url= http://genedeitch.awn.com/ | title= How To Succeed in Animation | publisher= [[Animation World Network]] | first= Gene | last= Deitch | date= November 18, 2013 | accessdate= October 29, 2015 | archivedate= October 22, 2015 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151022180650/http://www.awn.com/genedeitch | url-status= dead }} (Online instructional course)\n*{{cite web| url = http://www.cartoonhalloffame.org/2005/12/deitch-gene.html |title=Deitch, Gene| publisher= [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] Animation Archive: Cartoon Hall of Fame| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504025553/http://www.cartoonhalloffame.org/2005/12/deitch-gene.html|archivedate= May 4, 2012}} <!--Note: Despite the imprimatur of ASIFA-Hollywood, this is written by a pseudonymous user and so cannot be cited as footnoted reference-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deitch, Gene}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Czech animators]]\n[[Category:Czech comics artists]]\n[[Category:Czech illustrators]]\n[[Category:Czech children's book illustrators]]\n[[Category:Animators from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Czech animated film directors]]\n[[Category:Czech animated film producers]]\n[[Category:Artists from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Terrytoons]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Directors of Best Animated Short Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:Jewish artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American illustrator, animator and film director}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Gene Deitch.jpg\n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = Gene Deitch in 2007\n| name               = Gene Deitch\n| birth_name         = Eugene Merril Deitch\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1924|8|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], {{nowrap|United States}}\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|4|16|1924|8|8}}\n| death_place        = [[Prague]], {{nowrap|[[Czech Republic]]}}\n| nationality        = [[American people|American]]\n| spouse             = Marie Deitch (m. 1943\u2013?)<br>Zdenka Deitchova (n\u00e9e Najmanov\u00e1; m. 1964)\n| children           = 3 (including [[Kim Deitch]])\n| occupation         = Illustrator, animator, director\n| years_active       = 1945\u20132008\n| website            = [https://web.archive.org/web/20180215153432/http://www.genedeitch.com/ Archived at archive.org]\n}}\n'''Eugene Merril Deitch''' (August 8, 1924 \u2013 April 16, 2020) was an [[Americans|American]]-born [[Czech Republic|Czech]] illustrator, [[animator]], comics artist,<ref>https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm</ref> and film director. Based in [[Prague]] since 1959, Deitch was known for creating [[animated cartoon]]s such as ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'', ''[[Tom Terrific]]'', and ''[[Nudnik]]'', as well as his work on the ''[[Popeye]]'' and ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' series.\n\n==Early life==\nDeitch was born in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]] on August 8, 1924, the son of salesman Joseph Deitch and Ruth Delson Deitch.<ref name=\"Lenburg\">{{cite book|last=Lenburg|first=Jeff|title=Who's Who in Animated Cartoons|publisher=[[Applause Theatre and Cinema Books]]|location=New York City|year=2006|edition=Illustrated|pages=[https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/62 62\u201364]|isbn=978-1-55783-671-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinanimate0000lenb/page/62}}</ref><ref name=NCSML>{{cite web | url = http://www.ncsml.org/exhibits/gene-deitch/ | title = Gene Deitch (born Eugene Merril Deitch), 1924 | publisher = National Czech and Slovak Museum | accessdate = November 6, 2015 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150912101818/http://www.ncsml.org/exhibits/gene-deitch/ | archivedate = September 12, 2015 | url-status = dead }}</ref> In 1929, the family moved to California, and Deitch attended school in [[Hollywood]]. He graduated from [[Los Angeles High School]] in 1942.\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating, Deitch began working for [[North American Aviation]], drawing aircraft blueprints. In 1943, he was [[military conscription|drafted]] and underwent pilot training before catching [[pneumonia]] and being honorably discharged in May of the following year.<ref name=NCSML /> From 1945 to 1951, Deitch contributed covers and interior art to the [[jazz]] magazine ''The Record Changer''.<ref name=NCSML /> In the 1950s, Deitch was an early supporter and audio engineer for [[Connie Converse]], one of the first American [[singer-songwriter]]s.<ref name=\"The Awl 2010\">{{cite news | url=http://www.theawl.com/2010/08/the-story-of-connie-converse | title=The Story of Connie Converse | date=August 3, 2010 | accessdate=1 June 2013 | last=Jefferson | first=Cord | newspaper=The Awl}}</ref> Converse appeared once on [[CBS]] television due in part to Deitch's connections with the network, but otherwise found little success and eventually abandoned music only to be rediscovered decades later, through recordings Deitch had made of her music in 1954.\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Gene Deitch in 1959.jpg|thumb|Gene Deitch in 1959]] -->\nIn 1955, Deitch took a apprenticeship at the animation studio [[United Productions of America]] (UPA), and later became the creative director of [[Terrytoons]],<ref name=NCSML /> creating such characters as [[Sidney the Elephant]],<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/sidney.htm Sidney the Elephant] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vi9yM3C0?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/sidney.htm |date=January 20, 2015 }} from the original on January 20, 2015.</ref> [[Gaston Le Crayon]],<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/lecrayon.htm Gaston Le Crayon] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/66xEV3BXC?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/lecrayon.htm |date=April 16, 2012 }} from the original on April 16, 2012.</ref> and [[Clint Clobber]].<ref>[http://www.toonopedia.com/clobber.htm Clint  Clobber] at  [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/66vv3sglC?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/clobber.htm |date=April 15, 2012 }} from the original on April 16, 2012.</ref> Beginning in 1955, while working at UPA, Deitch wrote and drew the [[United Feature Syndicate]] comic strip ''The Real-Great Adventures of Terr\u2019ble Thompson!, Hero of History'', starring a courageous child in fantastical adventures. A skit about Terr'ble Thompson had been recorded by [[Little Golden Records]], with actor [[Art Carney]] and bandleader [[Mitch Miller]] participating. That led to the daily strip, which ran from Sunday, October 16, 1955, to April 14, 1956.<ref name=thompson>[http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm ''The Real-Great Adventures of Terr\u2019ble Thompson!, Hero of History''] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]].  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6fEh3AEBM?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |date=February 12, 2016 }} from the original on February 12, 2016.</ref> In early 1958, his theatrical cartoon ''Sidney's Family Tree'' was nominated for an Academy Award. In August 1958, he was fired from Terrytoons and set up his own studio in New York called Gene Deitch Associates, Inc., which primarily produced television commercials.<ref name=NCSML /> \n\nWhen client [[Rembrandt Films]]<ref name=WSJ/> promised to fund ''[[Munro (film)|Munro]]'', an animated theatrical short Deitch wanted to create, Deitch relocated to the company's base in [[Prague]], [[Czechoslovakia]], in October 1959.<ref name=NCSML /> He originally planned to spend only ten days in Prague, but after meeting his future wife, Zdena, decided to settle permanently in the city.<ref name=DVTV /> ''Munro'' premiered in Czechoslovakia in September 1960 and in the U.S. on October 5, 1961, as a short preceding ''[[Breakfast at Tiffany's (film)|Breakfast at Tiffany's]]''. It won an [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Animated Short Film|Animated Short Film]] in 1961,<ref>{{cite web|title=The 33rd Academy Awards|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1961|publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]|accessdate=November 6, 2015 | quote= Short Subject (Cartoon): Winner - ''Munro'', William L. Snyder, Producer| archivedate=October 15, 2015 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015234831/http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1961 | url-status=live}}</ref> the first short created outside of the United States to be so honored.<ref>[http://www.genedeitch.com/ \"Anatomy of an Oscar\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050303173042/http://www.genedeitch.com/ |date=March 3, 2005 }} ''Occasional Deitch'' 2007, page 3, retrieved [2007-11-04].</ref>\n\nFrom 1960 to 1963, Deitch collaborated with Rembrandt to direct ''[[Popeye the Sailor (1960s TV series)|Popeye]]'' cartoons for television with [[King Features Syndicate|King Features]], and from 1961 to 1962 he directed 13 new ''[[Tom and Jerry]]'' shorts for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]].<ref name=WSJ>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/djreprints/access/108884830.html?dids=108884830:108884830&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun+11%2C+1962&author=&pub=Wall+Street+Journal&desc=Popeye%2C+Tom+%26+Jerry+Join+Trend+to+Shift+Production+Overseas&pqatl=google|title=Popeye, Tom & Jerry Join Trend to Shift Production Overseas|accessdate=August 17, 2010|date=June 11, 1962|author=MacDougall, Kent|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Lehman\">{{cite book|title=American Animated Cartoons of the Vietnam Era: A Study of Social Commentary in Films and Television Programs, 1961\u20131973|first=P. Lehman|last=Christopher|isbn=978-0-7864-2818-2|chapter=The Cartoons of 1961\u20131962|pages=23\u201324|publisher=[[McFarland & Company]]|year=2007}}</ref> Being a \"UPA man\",<ref name=\"Deitch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.awn.com/genedeitch/chapter-twentyone-tom-and-jerry-the-first-reincarnation|title=Tom & Jerry: The First Reincarnation|work=How To Succeed in Animation|publisher=[[Animation World Network]]|year=2001|last=Deitch|first=Gene|accessdate=September 27, 2009 | archivedate= September 14, 2014| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140914223444/http://www.awn.com/genedeitch/chapter-twentyone-tom-and-jerry-the-first-reincarnation | url-status=live}}</ref> Deitch had misgivings about the latter property, thinking they were \"needlessly violent.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\"/> However, after being assigned to work on the series, he quickly realized that \"nobody took [the violence] seriously\", and it was merely \"a parody of exaggerated human emotions.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\">{{cite video |people=Deitch, Gene |date=2015 |title=''Tom and Jerry...and Gene'' in Tom and Jerry: The Gene Deitch Collection |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> He also came to see what he perceived as the \"biblical roots\" in Tom and Jerry's conflict, similar to [[David and Goliath]], stating \"That's where we feel a connection to these cartoons: the little guy can win (or at least survive) to fight another day.\"<ref name=\"DeitchDVD\"/> Contemporary critics often regarded Deitch's shorts as the worst in the ''Tom and Jerry'' series; however, Deitch claims some fans wrote positive letters to him, stating that his ''Tom and Jerry'' shorts were their personal favorites.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rotoscopers.com/2015/06/21/tom-and-jerry-the-gene-deitch-collection-dvd-review/ | title=\u2018Tom and Jerry: The Gene Deitch Collection\u2019 \u2013 DVD Review| publisher= Rotoscopers.com | first= Jonathan |last=North |date= June 21, 2015|accessdate= November 6, 2015| archivedate= September 12, 2015| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912040746/http://www.rotoscopers.com/2015/06/21/tom-and-jerry-the-gene-deitch-collection-dvd-review/ | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith producer [[William L. Snyder]], Deitch co-produced and directed a series of TV shorts of ''[[Krazy Kat]]'' for King Features from 1962 to 1964. ''[[The Bluffers]]'', which was based on one of Deitch's ideas, was also co-produced by him. He directed the 1966 film ''[[Alice of Wonderland in Paris]]''. In 1966, he worked with Czech animator [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Trnka]] on a feature-length animated film adapatation of ''[[The Hobbit]]''. However, producer William L. Snyder couldn't secure the funds, and in order to not let the rights for the novel expire, he asked Deitch to produce a short film adaptation in 30 days. Deitch and illustrator [[Adolf Born]] made a 13-minute animated film never intended for distribution; the film was long considered lost until it was rediscovered by Snyder's son and released on [[YouTube]] in 2012.<ref name=DVTV>{{cite web|url=https://video.aktualne.cz/dvtv/jsi-bud-komunista-nebo-blazen-slychaval-ceskoslovensko-bylo/r~a96bd4a84c8211e880d30cc47ab5f122/?redirected=1526714757|title=Jsi bu\u010f komunista, nebo bl\u00e1zen, sl\u00fdch\u00e1val. \u010ceskoslovensko bylo jako st\u0159edov\u011bk, l\u00ed\u010d\u00ed dr\u017eitel Oscara / 'You are either a communist or a fool': Czechoslovakia was like the Middle Ages, says the Oscar winner| publisher=[[DVTV]]| date= n.d.|accessdate=May 19, 2018|location=Czech Republic|language=czech}}</ref> Also in 1966, Deitch created a young girl adventurer in ''Terr'ble Tessie.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6fEh3AEBM?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/terrble.htm |archivedate=February 12, 2016 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1969 until his retirement in 2008, Deitch was the leading animation director for the Connecticut organization [[Weston Woods Studios]], adapting children's picture books. Deitch adapted 37 films for Weston Woods, from [[Drummer Hoff|''Drummer Hoff'']] in 1969 to ''Voyage to the Bunny Planet'' in 2008.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cech, John.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/310398653|title=Imagination and innovation : the story of Weston Woods|date=2009|publisher=Scholastic Press|isbn=978-0-545-08922-7|edition=1st ed|location=New York|oclc=310398653}}</ref> His studio was located in Prague near the [[Barrandov Studios]], where many major films were recorded. In 2003, Deitch was awarded the [[Annie Award]]s' [[Winsor McCay Award]] by [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] for a lifetime contribution to the art of animation.<ref name=\"McCayRecipient\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/winsor-mccay-award |title=Winsor McCay Award |publisher=[[Annie Award]]s / [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] |accessdate=November 3, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712035848/http://annieawards.org/winsor-mccay-award |archivedate=July 12, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nDeitch met his first wife, Marie, when they both worked at North American Aviation, and they married in 1943.<ref name=NCSML /> Their three sons,<ref name=NCSML /> [[Kim Deitch|Kim]], [[Simon Deitch|Simon]], and Seth Deitch, are artists and writers for [[underground comix]] and [[alternative comics]].<ref name=lam-kim>{{cite web |url=http://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch.htm |title=Kim Deitch |website=[[Lambiek Comiclopedia]] |access-date=November 12, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907063815/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch.htm |archive-date=September 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1960, several days after arriving in Prague in October 1959, Deitch met Zdenka Najmanov\u00e1, the production manager at the studio [[Brat\u0159i v triku]] where he worked. They married in 1964.<ref name=NCSML /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.novinky.cz/zena/styl/469454-gene-deitch-ze-bych-zustal-v-ceskoslovensku-zit-tehdy-nikoho-nenapadlo.html| title=Gene Deitch: \u017de bych z\u016fstal v \u010ceskoslovensku \u017e\u00edt, tehdy nikoho nenapadlo / Gene Deitch: I would live in Czechoslovakia, then did not think anyone| date=May 5, 2018|accessdate=May 19, 2018|first=Lucie |last=Jandov\u00e1|work=[[Pr\u00e1vo]]|location=Czech Republic|language=czech| via=Novinky.cz|archivedate=May 5, 2018|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20180505080129/https://www.novinky.cz/zena/styl/469454-gene-deitch-ze-bych-zustal-v-ceskoslovensku-zit-tehdy-nikoho-nenapadlo.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Deitch's memoir, ''For the Love of Prague,'' is based on his experience of being what he called \"the only free American living and working in Prague during 30 years of the Communist Party dictatorship.\"<ref>Deitch, G., [http://www.praguepost.com/142-culture/51247-gene-deitch-s-memoir-is-back ''For the Love of Prague''], 6th edition (Prague: John Caullkins, 2015).</ref> According to Deitch, although he was followed by the [[StB]] and his phone was tapped, he was never aware of their presence and was never interrogated nor arrested.<ref name=DVTV />\n\nDeitch died of natural causes in Prague on April 16, 2020, at the age of 95.<ref>[https://news.expats.cz/weekly-czech-news/american-animator-longtime-prague-expat-gene-deitch-passes-away-at-age-95/ American animator, longtime Prague expat Gene Deitch passes away at age 95]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\nKevin Scott Collier. ''The Amazing Transformations of Tom Terrific''. CreateSpace Independent Publishing Platform, 2017. {{ISBN|1974583899}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.genedeitch.com}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20150801130220/http://genedeitch.com/ Archived] from the original on August 1, 2015,\n*[http://www.genedeitchcredits.com/ Gene Deitch Credits] (additional official site) [https://web.archive.org/web/20150922191020/http://genedeitchcredits.com/ Archived] from the original on September 22, 2015.\n*{{IMDb name|id=0215126|name=Gene Deitch}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150908062347/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm Gene Deitch] at the Lambiek Comiclopedia. Retrieved on November 6, 2013. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150908062347/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm Archived] at the Lambiek Comiclopedia. Retrieved on November 6, 2013. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150908062347/https://www.lambiek.net/artists/d/deitch-gene.htm Archived] from the original on September 8, 2015.\n*{{cite web| url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/brewtv/howdydoody-22435.html | author= [[Jerry Beck|Beck, Jerry]], and Amidi, Amid, eds. | publisher= [[Cartoon Brew]] | title= TV #22: 'Howdy Doody and His Magic Hat' (1953)| date= April 15, 2010| accessdate= October 29, 2015| archivedate= March 8, 2012 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120308104239/http://www.cartoonbrew.com/brewtv/howdydoody.html | url-status=live}} Includes biographical sidebar by Deitch.\n*{{cite web | url= http://genedeitch.awn.com/ | title= How To Succeed in Animation | publisher= [[Animation World Network]] | first= Gene | last= Deitch | date= November 18, 2013 | accessdate= October 29, 2015 | archivedate= October 22, 2015 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20151022180650/http://www.awn.com/genedeitch | url-status= dead }} (Online instructional course)\n*{{cite web| url = http://www.cartoonhalloffame.org/2005/12/deitch-gene.html |title=Deitch, Gene| publisher= [[ASIFA-Hollywood]] Animation Archive: Cartoon Hall of Fame| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504025553/http://www.cartoonhalloffame.org/2005/12/deitch-gene.html|archivedate= May 4, 2012}} <!--Note: Despite the imprimatur of ASIFA-Hollywood, this is written by a pseudonymous user and so cannot be cited as footnoted reference-->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deitch, Gene}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Czech animators]]\n[[Category:Czech comics artists]]\n[[Category:Czech illustrators]]\n[[Category:Czech children's book illustrators]]\n[[Category:Animators from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Czech animated film directors]]\n[[Category:Czech animated film producers]]\n[[Category:Artists from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Terrytoons]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Directors of Best Animated Short Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:Jewish artists]]\n", "name_user": "TMProofreader", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene_Deitch"}
{"title_page": "Rubberman (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|Philippine superhero film}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Rubberman\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = Edgardo Vinarao\n| producer       = Art R. Ilacad\n| screenplay     = Cris Pablo\n| story          = Michael V.\n| starring       = [[Michael V.]]\n| music          = Jessie Lasaten\n| cinematography = Jun Perreira\n| editing        = Edgardo Vinarao\n| studio         = {{ubl|[[OctoArts Films]]|[[GMA Films|Cinemax Studios]]}}\n| distributor    = OctoArts Films\n| released       = {{Film date|1996|12|25}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = Philippines\n| language       = {{ubl|Filipino|English}}\n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Rubberman: Up, Up and Away''''' is a [[Philippine film|Philippine]] [[Comedy film|comedy]] [[Superhero film|superhero]] film directed by Edgardo Vinarao. The film stars [[Michael V.]] as the title role. It was one of the entries in the [[1996 Metro Manila Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=d_oMAQAAMAAJ|title=Filipinas: Vol. 12|pages=50|date=2003|publisher=Filipinas Publications|accessdate=April 17, 2020|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internationalhero.co.uk/p/phrubman.htm|title=Rubberman from the Philippines|website=International Superheroes|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/the-freeman/cebu-entertainment/2019/07/30/1939014/how-be-comedian-according-michael-v|title=How to be a comedian according to Michael V|website=[[The Philippine Star]]|date=July 30, 2019|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://video48.blogspot.com/2010/10/1996-metro-manila-film-festival-amy.html|title=The 1996 Metro Manila Film Festival|website=Video 48|date=October 10, 2010|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Michael V.]] as Bitoy / Rubberman\n* Beth Tamayo as Jessica\n* [[Gloria Romero (actress)|Gloria Romero]] as Madam Rita\n* [[Dick Israel]] as Val Balbin / Mandreko\n* [[Roy Alvarez]] as Yoyoy\n* [[Allan K.]] as Baldo\n* [[Bomber Moran]] as Bobo\n* Archie Adamos as Video Guy\n* Nathan Torres as Henry\n* [[Tootsie Guevara]] as Carissa\n* Tonee Arao as Tonee\n* Randel Gayoso as Jeff\n* Dina Cementina as Carnival Manager\n* Princess Ann Schuck as Little Jessica\n* Emman Abeleda as Younger Brother\n* [[Ian Veneracion]] as Police in Shootout\n* Jennifer Mendoza as TV News Field Reporter\n* Lara Morena  as Roller Blade Girl\n* [[Jun Limpot]] as himself\n* [[Vergel Meneses]] as herself\n* Aster Amoyo as himself\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0379968}}\n\n[[Category:1996 films]]\n[[Category:Filipino-language films]]\n[[Category:GMA Pictures films]]\n[[Category:OctoArts Films films]]\n[[Category:Philippine films]]\n[[Category:Philippine action films]]\n[[Category:Philippine comedy films]]\n[[Category:Philippine fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Philippine superhero films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Philippine superhero film}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Rubberman\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = Edgardo Vinarao\n| producer       = Art R. Ilacad\n| screenplay     = Cris Pablo\n| story          = Michael V.\n| starring       = [[Michael V.]]\n| music          = Jessie Lasaten\n| cinematography = Jun Perreira\n| editing        = Edgardo Vinarao\n| studio         = {{ubl|[[OctoArts Films]]|[[GMA Films|Cinemax Studios]]}}\n| distributor    = OctoArts Films\n| released       = {{Film date|1996|12|25}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = Philippines\n| language       = {{ubl|Filipino|English}}\n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Rubberman: Up, Up and Away''''' is a [[Philippine film|Philippine]] [[Comedy film|comedy]] [[Superhero film|superhero]] film directed by Edgardo Vinarao. The film stars [[Michael V.]] as the title role. It was one of the entries in the [[1996 Metro Manila Film Festival]].<ref>{