ogle.com/forum/#!topic/alt.obituaries/dzjmaMOrDUA</ref>\n* [[Air Vice-Marshal]] [[Ronald Knott]], [[Order of the Bath|CB]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]], [[Air Force Cross (United Kingdom)|AFC]] and [[Medal Bar|Bar]], [[RAF]], Station Commander of [[RAF G\u00fctersloh]], 1959\u201361<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PKIWAQAAIAAJ&q=knott+borden+grammar&dq=knott+borden+grammar&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiggZvHgcDoAhWkoFwKHZoDAdkQ6AEIJjAA</ref><ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1417202/Air-Vice-Marshal-Ronnie-Knott.html</ref><ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/air-vice-marshal-ronald-knott-8f8xf5g877j</ref>\n* [[Jason Lee (field hockey)|Jason Lee]], field hockey coach and former international player\n* [[Commodore (Royal Navy)|Commodore]] [[Douglas Littlejohns]], [[CBE]], [[Royal Navy|RN]], [[Royal Navy Submarine Service|submarine commander]], adviser to [[Tom Clancy|Tom Clancy's]] [[Red Storm Rising]] and former CEO of [[Red Storm Entertainment]]<ref>https://uk.linkedin.com/in/doug-littlejohns-46a54b13</ref>\n* [[Colonel]] [[Brian Luck]], [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], late [[Royal Artillery]], Commander Royal Artillery [[Gibraltar]], 1925-26<ref>School Admissions Register</ref><ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pFEMAQAAMAAJ&q=brian+luck+cmg+dso+colonel&dq=brian+luck+cmg+dso+colonel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjV99fnydjoAhVQTcAKHaz_C9EQ6AEISzAF</ref>\n* Hon. [[Brigadier-General]] [[Cyril Montagu Luck]], [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], late [[Royal Engineers]], Director-General of Inland Water Transport, France, 1917-19<ref>School Admissions Register</ref><ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FBU2AQAAMAAJ&q=cyril+luck+cmg+dso+brigadier&dq=cyril+luck+cmg+dso+brigadier&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi3tsqLydjoAhXRUMAKHexsARMQ6AEIRTAE</ref>\n* [[Sean McGinty]], professional footballer\n* [[Peter Millican]], philosopher<ref>http://millican.org/about.htm</ref>\n* [[Brigadier]] [[Noel Muddiman]], [[CBE]], late [[Royal Corps of Transport]], Commander Transport and Movements, [[First Gulf War]]; former director of [[Motability]]<ref>https://doi.org/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U28407</ref><ref>https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2003-07-08/debates/65a1d91c-752f-4450-b046-d668a3320750/Motability</ref>\n* Sir [[Alfred Road]], [[CBE]], Chief Inspector of Taxes, [[Inland Revenue]], 1952-56<ref>https://doi.org/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U158992</ref><ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PKIWAQAAIAAJ&q=sir+alfred+road+borden+grammar&dq=sir+alfred+road+borden+grammar&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiryNCVgcDoAhVUilwKHWytAzsQ6AEIMzAC</ref><ref>https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp78841/sir-alfred-road</ref>\n* [[Nicholas Sims-Williams]], [[British Academy|FBA]], Emeritus Professor of [[Iranian Studies|Iranian]] and [[Central Asian Studies]], [[SOAS]]<ref>https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/fellows/nicholas-sims-williams-FBA</ref>\n* [[Patrick Sims-Williams]], [[British Academy|FBA]], Emeritus Professor of [[Celtic Studies]], [[Aberystwyth University]]<ref>https://doi.org/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U34970</ref><ref>https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/fellows/patrick-sims-williams-FBA</ref>\n* [[Michael Smith (newspaper reporter)|Michael Smith]], author\n*[[Nicholas Vincent]], [[British Academy|FBA]], Professor of [[Middle Ages|Medieval History]], [[University of East Anglia]]<ref>https://doi.org/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U251481</ref><ref>https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/fellows/nicholas-vincent-FBA</ref>\n* [[Edward Wakeford]], [[geometry|geometer]]<ref>School Admissions Register</ref><ref>https://www.iwm.org.uk/memorials/item/memorial/84426</ref>\n* Sir [[Cecil Wakeley]], 1st [[Wakeley baronets|Baronet]] of Liss, [[KBE]], [[Order of the Bath|CB]], [[FRCS]], President of the [[Royal College of Surgeons of England]], 1949-54; [[Royal Navy Medical Service|Surgeon Rear-Admiral]], [[Royal Navy]]<ref>School Admissions Register</ref>\n* [[George Zucco]], character actor<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=m5OHAAAAIAAJ&q=zucco+borden+grammar&dq=zucco+borden+grammar&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjFnJysgcDoAhUNT8AKHZRnAP8Q6AEIODAC</ref><ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=m5OHAAAAIAAJ&q=george+zucco+borden+school&dq=george+zucco+borden+school&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj_gYDqs7roAhXTi1wKHU0wCFwQ6AEIODAC</ref>\n\n== Notable former staff ==\n* [[Robert Ladds]] (Chemistry teacher), [[Bishop of Whitby]], 1999-2008\n\n== Notable people associated with Borden Grammar School ==\n*Sir [[Edward Leigh Pemberton]], [[Order of the Bath|KCB]], [[Justice of the Peace|JP]], [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]], first chair of governors<ref>https://old-bordenians.bordengrammar.kent.sch.uk/index.php/down-memory-lane/16-founding-a-school-in-the-1870s-part-i</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n{{Schools in Kent}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1878]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in Kent]]\n[[Category:Sittingbourne]]\n[[Category:Grammar schools in Kent]]\n[[Category:1878 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Academies in Kent]]\n[[Category:People educated at Borden Grammar School|*]]\n", "name_user": "Old Bordenian", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Borden_Grammar_School"}
{"title_page": "Red Rat", "text_new": "{{Use Jamaican English|date=January 2015}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{about||the red rat snake|Corn snake}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2011}}\n'''Wallace Wilson''' (born 17 January 1978), better known by the [[stage name]] '''Red Rat''', is a [[Jamaica]]n [[Dancehall|dancehall reggae]] recording and performing artist.<ref name=\"Kellman\">Kellman, Andy \"[http://www.allmusic.com/artist/red-rat-p279232/biography Red Rat Biography]\", [[Allmusic]], retrieved 2011-02-15</ref>  He is known for his up-beat music, comical style, and signature catch phrase \"Oh, no!\"\n\nHis favourite past time is smokin a lil twenny twen twen with the boys Gearle and mowg\n\n== Early life ==\nWilson was born in Saint Ann's Bay, [[Saint Ann Parish]], [[Jamaica]].<ref name=\"Kellman\" />\n\nWilson's father was the guitarist of [[Byron Lee & the Dragonaires]], and two of his older brothers were also professional musicians.<ref name=\"Kellman\" />\n\nRed Rat's debut album, ''Oh, No.. It's Red Rat'' (1997), featured songs such as \"Shelly Ann\", \"Dwayne\", \"Tight-up Skirt\", \"Cruise\" (featured in the movie ''[[The Big Hit]]''), and \"Big Man, Little Yute\". It became one of the best selling records from [[Greensleeves Records]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}\n\nHis second album, ''I\u2019m a Big Kid Now'', followed in 2000,<ref name=\"Kellman\" /> with more hits and critical acclaim. His musical diversity and mainstream popularity led to a series of collaborations with artists such as Treach of Naughty by Nature, Kele Le Roc, Renee from Zhane, NEXT, British icons [[Groove Armada]] and his cousin, Canadian hip-hop artist, [[Dan-e-o]]. Recently, Red Rat reemerged back in the media with his new hit, \"Rise up, Zimbabwe\" which was a joint project with ABRA (African Bread Recording Artists). The song was released in April 2010 and immediately saw popularity in the music fans of Zimbabwe.\n\nIn 2009, Red Rat rebranded himself and was offered an opportunity to become the President of A&R/ Musical Director at an independent record label called Infinity Moguls Inc. He began working with a young female artist named Pascalle, who is his business partner with Infinity Moguls. Pascalle performed with him all over the world. He began to coach her personally. Red Rat then went on to collaborate with Dan-e-o, his cousin, a Toronto-based rapper, the song also featured Pascalle, called \"Hoo Yuh Want?\" Followed by Red Rat, Infinity Moguls teamed up with ABRA in 2010, for the release of \"Rise Up, Zimbabwe\" which became an anthem. Red Rat revisited the [[Central America]] market, where Infinity Moguls partnered with Ruff and Tuff on another song that became Pascalle's single \"HAUTE\" featuring Red Rat and Toledo. The song was released in 2016, and quickly topped the Caribbean charts.\n\nIn 2016 Red Rat teamed up with DJ Buddha to create an [[Electronic dance music|EDM]]/[[Dancehall]]/Mumbaton fused song called \"Higher\" featuring an up-and-coming artist dEvolve which was released in September 2016 and became one of the fastest song to get over three million streams on [[Spotify]] in less than three months.\n\n==Discography==\n*''Oh, No.. It's Red Rat'' (1997), [[Greensleeves Records|Greensleeves]]\n*''I'm a Big Kid Now'' (2000), Greensleeves\n*''Monsters of Dancehall'' (2008), Greensleeves\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.redrat.com/}}\n* [http://www.InfinityMoguls.com Infinity Moguls]\n*{{Cite web|url=https://myspace.com/red_rat|title=Wallace Wilson (red_rat) on Myspace|website=Myspace|access-date=2020-01-04}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.last.fm/music/Red+Rat/+wiki|title=Red Rat age, hometown, biography|website=Last.fm|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red Rat}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dancehall musicians]]\n[[Category:Jamaican reggae musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Saint Ann Parish]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Jamaican English|date=January 2015}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{about||the red rat snake|Corn snake}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2011}}\n'''Wallace Wilson''' (born 17 January 1978), better known by the [[stage name]] '''Red Rat''', is a [[Jamaica]]n [[Dancehall|dancehall reggae]] recording and performing artist.<ref name=\"Kellman\">Kellman, Andy \"[http://www.allmusic.com/artist/red-rat-p279232/biography Red Rat Biography]\", [[Allmusic]], retrieved 2011-02-15</ref>  He is known for his up-beat music, comical style, and signature catch phrase \"Oh, no!\"\n\n== Early life ==\nWilson was born in Saint Ann's Bay, [[Saint Ann Parish]], [[Jamaica]].<ref name=\"Kellman\" />\n\nWilson's father was the guitarist of [[Byron Lee & the Dragonaires]], and two of his older brothers were also professional musicians.<ref name=\"Kellman\" />\n\nRed Rat's debut album, ''Oh, No.. It's Red Rat'' (1997), featured songs such as \"Shelly Ann\", \"Dwayne\", \"Tight-up Skirt\", \"Cruise\" (featured in the movie ''[[The Big Hit]]''), and \"Big Man, Little Yute\". It became one of the best selling records from [[Greensleeves Records]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}\n\nHis second album, ''I\u2019m a Big Kid Now'', followed in 2000,<ref name=\"Kellman\" /> with more hits and critical acclaim. His musical diversity and mainstream popularity led to a series of collaborations with artists such as Treach of Naughty by Nature, Kele Le Roc, Renee from Zhane, NEXT, British icons [[Groove Armada]] and his cousin, Canadian hip-hop artist, [[Dan-e-o]]. Recently, Red Rat reemerged back in the media with his new hit, \"Rise up, Zimbabwe\" which was a joint project with ABRA (African Bread Recording Artists). The song was released in April 2010 and immediately saw popularity in the music fans of Zimbabwe.\n\nIn 2009, Red Rat rebranded himself and was offered an opportunity to become the President of A&R/ Musical Director at an independent record label called Infinity Moguls Inc. He began working with a young female artist named Pascalle, who is his business partner with Infinity Moguls. Pascalle performed with him all over the world. He began to coach her personally. Red Rat then went on to collaborate with Dan-e-o, his cousin, a Toronto-based rapper, the song also featured Pascalle, called \"Hoo Yuh Want?\" Followed by Red Rat, Infinity Moguls teamed up with ABRA in 2010, for the release of \"Rise Up, Zimbabwe\" which became an anthem. Red Rat revisited the [[Central America]] market, where Infinity Moguls partnered with Ruff and Tuff on another song that became Pascalle's single \"HAUTE\" featuring Red Rat and Toledo. The song was released in 2016, and quickly topped the Caribbean charts.\n\nIn 2016 Red Rat teamed up with DJ Buddha to create an [[Electronic dance music|EDM]]/[[Dancehall]]/Mumbaton fused song called \"Higher\" featuring an up-and-coming artist dEvolve which was released in September 2016 and became one of the fastest song to get over three million streams on [[Spotify]] in less than three months.\n\n==Discography==\n*''Oh, No.. It's Red Rat'' (1997), [[Greensleeves Records|Greensleeves]]\n*''I'm a Big Kid Now'' (2000), Greensleeves\n*''Monsters of Dancehall'' (2008), Greensleeves\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.redrat.com/}}\n* [http://www.InfinityMoguls.com Infinity Moguls]\n*{{Cite web|url=https://myspace.com/red_rat|title=Wallace Wilson (red_rat) on Myspace|website=Myspace|access-date=2020-01-04}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.last.fm/music/Red+Rat/+wiki|title=Red Rat age, hometown, biography|website=Last.fm|language=en|access-date=2020-01-04}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red Rat}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dancehall musicians]]\n[[Category:Jamaican reggae musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Saint Ann Parish]]\n", "name_user": "86.30.148.204", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Hobby)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Rat"}
{"title_page": "Champion (sportswear)", "text_new": "{{Other uses2|Champion}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Champion\n| logo                = File:ChampionLogo.png\n| industry            = Clothing\n| location_city       = [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]]\n| location_country    = United States\n| locations           = 28 stores (2018)<ref>{{Cite web\n |url=https://stores.champion.com/\n |title=Champion stores in the United States\n |publisher=william lyle\n\n |date=2018\n |access-date=17 Jan 2020\n}}{{self-published source}}</ref>\n| area_served         = {{flat list|\n* [[North America]]\n* [[Europe]]\n* [[Asia]]\n* [[Wakanda]]\n}}\n| key_people          = \n| products            = {{flat list|\n* [[Clothing]]\n* [[Sportswear (activewear)|sportswear]]\n* [[footwear]]\n}}\n| revenue             = \n| parent              = [[Hanesbrands]]\n| homepage            = {{URL|champion.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Champion''' (or alternatively also stylized as '''Champion U.S.A.''') is an [[United States|American]] manufacturer of [[clothing]], specializing in [[Sportswear (activewear)|sportswear]]. The brand is a subsidiary of [[Hanesbrands]] (based in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina|Winston-Salem]], [[North Carolina]]), which was [[Corporate spin-off|spun off]] by the [[Sara Lee Corporation]] in 2006. The company was originally based in [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]], [[New York (state)|New York]], prior to its acquisition by Sara Lee in 1989.<ref name=\"tribune\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1989-02-14-8903050345-story.html|title=Sara Lee Adds Champion Sportswear To Wardrobe|last=Key|first=Janet|date=14 February 1989|work=Chicago Tribune|access-date=17 Jan 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n\"Champion\" is HanesBrands' second-largest brand with the namesake [[Hanes]] brand in first place. Other brands owned by HanesBrands Inc. are [[Playtex]] (its third-largest brand), [[Bali (lingerie)|Bali]], Just My Size, Barely There, [[Wonderbra]], [[L'eggs]], C9 by Champion, Duofold, Beefy-T, Outer Banks, Sol y Oro, Rinbros, Zorba and Ritmo.\n\n==History==\nThe company was established in 1919 by the Feinbloom brothers <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theidleman.com/manual/arrivals/brands/the-history-of-champion/|title=The History of Champion|last=|first=|date=13 November 2018|website=The Idle Man|type=Blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 Jan 2020}}</ref> as \"Knickerbocker Knitting Company.\" The company soon signed an agreement with the [[Michigan Wolverines]] to produce uniforms for their teams. In the 1930s the company was renamed \"Champion Knitting Mills Inc.\", producing [[Sweater|sweatshirts]]. Soon after, Champion products would be adopted by the [[United States Military Academy|US Military Academy]] to be used during training exercises and physical education classes.<ref name=champeu>[http://www.champion-eu.com/about-us About us] on Champion-eu website</ref>\n\nChampion was acquired by [[Sara Lee Corporation]] in 1989.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1989/02/14/business/champion-products-accepts-bid.html</ref> Champion produced uniforms for all the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] teams during the 1990s and some [[National Football League|NFL]] teams during the 1970s to the 1990s, for both on-field and retail purposes. It has also produced sportswear for many major colleges.<ref>{{Citation|last=JARochNY|title=Abraham and William Feinbloom, Champion Products, Inc.|date=2010-10-21|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sayHwiulUA0|accessdate=2018-06-05}}</ref> Champion was also the kit manufacturer of the [[1992 United States men's Olympic basketball team|Olympic basketball team]] that competed at the [[1992 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=champeu/>\n\nFrom the mid-1980s to the mid-1990s, it was a very common fashion trend to see girls and guys of all ages wearing Champion sweatshirts over a turtleneck and over jeans with slouch socks and sneakers. Girls of all ages and adults also wore the sweatshirts oversized or extra-long with leggings and slouch socks and athletic sneakers, [[Keds]] or boat shoes. Today, Champion is now considered a very well known brand.\n\nFrom 2008, Champion produced kits for [[Premier League]] side, [[Wigan Athletic]], the [[Wales national football team]] and the jersey of the [[Greece national basketball team|Greek basketball team]],<ref>[http://www.champion-eu.com/news/en/62180/2/Champion_opens_it_s_100th_store_in_Faenza_Italy.aspx Champion presents the new Greek national basketball team jersey] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708134003/http://www.champion-eu.com/news/en/62180/2/Champion_opens_it_s_100th_store_in_Faenza_Italy.aspx |date=July 8, 2011 }}</ref> also [[Pallacanestro Cant\u00f9]], in Italy.\n\nFor many years Champion supplied the athletic uniforms for the [[University of Notre Dame|Notre Dame]] [[Fighting Irish]]. In 2001 Notre Dame signed a five-year exclusive agreement with [[Adidas]], which ended a partnership Champion had with the university that spanned over 50 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://magazine.nd.edu/news/16179-adidas-allegiance/|title=Adidas allegiance // News // Notre Dame Magazine // University of Notre Dame|last=Dame|first=ENR/PAZ // University Communications: Web // University of Notre|website=magazine.nd.edu|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref>\n\n==Sponsorships==\n{{More citations needed section|date=December 2019}}\nChampion has manufactured and provided kit uniforms for the following teams and associations:\n\n===Current sponsorships===\n\n\n=====Associations=====\n* [[FIBA]]<ref>[http://www.fiba.com/pages/eng/fc/FIBA/PartSpon/p/openNodeIDs/899/selNodeID/899/offiSpon.html FIBA global partners], retrieved 31 Aug 2014</ref>\n* [[National Basketball League (Australia)]] (effective 2020-21 season)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nbl.com.au/news/champion-signs-up-as-nbl-on-court-apparel-partner |website=NBL.com.au |publisher=National Basketball League |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n=====National teams=====\n* {{Flag icon|Albania}} [[Albania national basketball team|Albania]]\n* {{Flag icon|South Africa}} [[South Africa national basketball team|South Africa]]\n\n=====Club teams=====\n* {{Flag icon|Serbia}} [[KK FMP Beograd|FMP]]\n* {{Flag icon|Croatia}} [[KK Zadar|Zadar]]\n* {{Flag icon|Serbia}} [[KK Dynamic|Dynamic VIP PAY]]\n\n====Lacrosse====\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[US Lacrosse|USA national team]]\n\n===Past sponsorships===\n====American/Canadian football====\n* {{Flag icon|USA}} [[XFL (2001)|XFL]] (2001)\n* {{Flag icon|CAN}} [[Canadian Football League|CFL]] (1987\u201389)\n\n====Basketball====\n* {{Flag icon|CAN}} {{Flag icon|USA}} [[NBA]] \u2013 all teams (1990\u20131997), select teams (1997\u20132006)\n* {{Flag icon|USA}} [[United States men's national basketball team|U.S. national team]] (1992\u20132000)\n* {{Flag icon|Cyprus}} [[Cyprus national basketball team|Cyprus national team]] (2015)<ref name=\"kit\">[http://www.basketball.org.cy/kok/default.aspx#fragment-3 Cyprus Basketball Federation], http://www.basketball.org.cy/, Retrieved 1 October 2015. {{in lang|el}}</ref>\n* {{Flag icon|ITA}} [[Italy national basketball team|Italy national team]] (1996\u20132016)\n* {{Flag icon|ITA}} [[Virtus Pallacanestro Bologna|Virtus Bologna]] (1999\u20132005)\n\n====Soccer====\n* {{Flag icon|ENG}} [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] (2008\u201309)\n* {{Flag icon|ITA}} [[Parma Calcio 1913|AC Parma]] (1999\u20132005, including the last season as main sponsor of the club)\n* {{Flag icon|Wales}} [[Wales national football team]] (2008\u201310)\n* {{Flag icon|FRA}} [[FC Sochaux-Montb\u00e9liard]] (2003\u201305, including the last season as main sponsor of the club)\n\n==Merchandising licensed manufacturer==\nThe following is a list of the products made by the company in the licensed sports business:\n\n===Replica jerseys===\n* {{Flag icon|CAN}} {{Flag icon|USA}} [[NBA]] \u2013 all teams (1990\u20132002)\n* {{Flag icon|USA}} [[NFL]] \u2013 all teams (1980s\u20132000)\n* {{Flag icon|USA}} [[XFL (2001)|XFL]] \u2013 all teams (2001)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.champion.com/ Official website]\n* [http://www.hanesbrands.com/ Hanes Brands]\n<!--======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia  |\n    | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n    |                                                                     |\n    |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.  |\n    |                                                                     |\n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or   |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n    | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org)   |\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.         |\n    |======================== {{No more links}} ==========================|\n-->\n{{HanesBrands}}\n{{Sports equipment brands}}\n{{Running shoe brands}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Champion (Sportswear)}}\n[[Category:Sara Lee Corporation brands]]\n[[Category:Clothing companies established in 1919]]\n[[Category:Sportswear brands]]\n[[Category:Clothing companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Sporting goods manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Winston-Salem, North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses2|Champion}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Champion\n| logo = File:ChampionLogo.png\n| industry = Clothing\n| location_city = [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]]\n| location_country = United States\n| locations = 28 stores (2018)<ref>{{Cite web\n |url=https://stores.champion.com/\n |title=Champion stores in the United States\n |publisher=william lyle\n\n |date=2018\n |access-date=17 Jan 2020\n}}{{